notes.aheadoftheherd.com: false quotes regarding banking, heavily promotes businesses advertising on site/ buying of precious metals
notes.americanthinker.com: sites both reliable/not reliable sources, mix of opinion/'fact'
notes.antiwar.com: site is biased but very open about bias and source
notes.conservativepapers.com: incorrect/uncited data, citing other sources labeled as bias
notes.conservativestate.com: links to other borderline fake, but mostly just propagandistic websites
notes.DeadlyClear.wordpress.com: not a personal website, owned by project maui, inc. makes unverifiable extraordinary claims, seems to be advertising for lawyers with a history of legal reprimands.
notes.debunkingskeptics.com: science doesn't mean what they think it means
notes.defenddemocracy.press: editorial board as stated on about us seem to be legitimate academics, and originally authored content byline are academics, although not able to find a clear link between edu pages and these authors' work on this website. many 3rd party articles are linked, sources provided. these articles are aggregated from other more clearly biased sites i.e. world socialist web site (wswg.org), rt.com, sputniknews.com.
notes.endtime.com: i would classify this as "religious clickbait," with all of its reporting coming through a fundamentalist christian filter-- thus the "extreme bias."
notes.extraclubmagazine.com: vacillates between outright fake and misleading stories
notes.frontpagemag.com: part of david horowitz' freedom center
notes.therealstrategy.com: black lives matter content spews a lot of racist info
notes.washingtonsblog.com: site notes it sometimes contains parody
notes.uslifetoday.com: doesn't appear to be currently updated
notes.cryptogon.com: copy-pasted commentary from various news & 'news' sources
notes.Dont-Tread-On.Me: doesn't seem to be updating anymore
notes.endoftheamericandream.com: traffics in religious conspiracy theories and poorly sourced pro-trump propaganda
notes.politicalblindspot.com: ex: vaccines are a way for the cia to spy on us
notes.conservativedailypost.com: this website is a weird mix of outright fake news and some stuff that looks more reliable.
notes.enabon.com: no authors, no contact, just copy/pasted from other questionable sites
notes.fakingnews.com: fiction disclaimer on bottom of home screen
notes.iwanttoexplore.com: mostly turned back into car website
notes.react365.com: fake news generator for pranking friends
notes.theracketreport.com: i can't find disclaimers, but i think it's satirical
notes.therightscoop.com: no authors, no history, no about us, unverifiable data, etc.
notes.thetruthseeker.co.uk: ex: ny orchestrated the asian tsunami in 2008!
notes.usainfobox.com: can't find satire disclaimer, patently false
notes.weeklyworldnews.com: pretty well known tabloid/fake news source
notes.yourfunpage.com: mostly links to rando yt videos
notes.FarmWars.info: much of the site is focused on anti-gmo conspiracies, with political conspiracies coming in as a close second. there are some apparent attempts to source some wild claims, but the use of unstable urls-- intentionally or otherwise-- thwarts this.
notes.baptistnews.com: circulates generally reliable information from a p.o.v. but not at the expense of informational integrity
notes.chroniclesmagazine.org: from what i gather, like the opposite of jacobin (paleoconservative)
notes.countercurrents.org: this site is pretty explicit about it's p.o.v. and is coming from a political perspective but doesn't fit under how we are defining 'bias'
notes.dailycaller.com: a weird mix of info. they link to extremely biased sites (as sources) and more reliable/balanced sources
notes.economicnoise.com: sites some problematic sources, like cns news
notes.ecowatch.com: this site claims junksci, but i read over a dozen articles w/o finding any. probably should re-check soon https://mediabiasfactcheck.com/ecowatch/
notes.foreignpolicyjournal.com: legit source coming from a political perspective
notes.geopolmonitor.com: this website is tricky (in terms of writers using some interesting frames/language). def could use a second analysis.
notes.mintpressnews.com: legit source form a political perspective
notes.nakedcapitalism.com: commentary on finance, economics, politics and power
notes.newcoldwar.org: contains statement that site authors are "independent, but not non-partisan" (anti-war (ukraine))
notes.observer.com: vacillates between some pieces that are "bias" and others that are "reliable"
notes.pjmedia.com: https://mediabiasfactcheck.com/pj-media/ ;  https://pjmedia.com/about-us (ground zero mosque, 'doctored climate change data')
notes.consortiumnews.com: the authors on this website are pretty reliable and the articles appear well researched
notes.nutritionfacts.org: i read through several articles and the sources cited, and appears ok (maybe sometimes a little sensational... so if anyone has specific knowledge of this site and/or good examples of problems, feel free to link them here)
notes.elkoshary.com: about me notes that it's not fake/satirical news
notes.elmundotoday.com: about me notes that it's not fake/satirical news
notes.newstoad.net: tagline: the news they don't want you to hear. because it isn't true.
notes.therightists.com: publishes both biased and fake content
notes.AutomaticEarth.com: links to msm sources and unreliable sources
notes.Boilingfrogspost.com: links to natural news, blacklist news, some conspiracy sites
notes.bvanews.com: seems like a combination of totally fake and unreliable reports of 'real' news
notes.CNSNews.com: the news arm of media research center (a conservative org that is frequently criticized for use of selective evidence)
notes.Mad-Yet.blogspot.com: links to real news stories, but also some questionable/decontextualized images
notes.morningnewsusa.com: stories seem to originate from real news, but are somewhat clickbait-y and sources are not cited
notes.shareblue.com: my analysis is similar to this site: https://mediabiasfactcheck.com/shareblue/
notes.usviewer.com: no authors listed or publication info"
notes.veteransnewsnow.com: i read sample articles and didn't find inaccuracy, but the language is strong/loaded
notes.WallStreetOnParade.com: mostly linking/commenting on both news and other sources.
notes.weaselzippers.us: copies/pastes quotes/bits from news orgs and other questionable sites
